 host of the Red team since Teru Miyata in the 6th and 7th editions. Red team hosts (even in pairs) are usually female.</span><br>\n<span style=\"font-size:87%;\">*** All five members of Arashi act as one host-unit, although at least one member would appear on stage to take the role. </span>\n\n==Popularity==\n''K\u014dhaku'' was once the most-watched show on Japanese television of the year. One major factor was that New Year's Eve in Japan is a holiday traditionally spent at home (see [[\u014cmisoka]]). Over the years, the annual event's popularity has declined from an all-time high of an 81.4 rating (14th event) to an all-time low of a 30.8/39.3 rating (55th event) in the [[Kant\u014d region]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.videor.co.jp/data/ratedata/program/01kouhaku.htm|title=NHK\u7dcf\u5408\u300c\u7d05\u767d\u6b4c\u5408\u6226\u300d - \u30d3\u30c7\u30aa\u30ea\u30b5\u30fc\u30c1|work=videor.co.jp|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050121012019/http://www.videor.co.jp/data/ratedata/program/01kouhaku.htm|archivedate=2005-01-21}}</ref> Despite the drop, ''K\u014dhaku'' is consistently the top-rated musical event each year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.videor.co.jp/data/ratedata/r_index.htm|title=\u8996\u8074\u7387\u30c7\u30fc\u30bf\uff5c\u30d3\u30c7\u30aa\u30ea\u30b5\u30fc\u30c1|work=videor.co.jp|access-date=2006-12-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061130083627/http://www.videor.co.jp/data/ratedata/r_index.htm|archive-date=2006-11-30|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Notable participants==\n=== Japanese entertainers ===\nThe following is a list of acts with notable contributions to the Japanese entertainment industry, and have a minimum of five appearances on ''K\u014dhaku'' to their credit (appearance numbers in parentheses are as of the 69th edition):\n\n==== Pop and rock ====\n{{Div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Attack All Around|AAA]] (7)\n* [[Ai Otsuka]] (6)\n* [[Aiko (singer)|Aiko]] (13)\n* [[AKB48]] (11)\n* [[Akina Nakamori]] (7)\n* [[Angela Aki]] (6)\n* [[Arashi]] (10)\n* [[Aya Matsuura]] (5)<sup>1</sup>\n* [[Ayaka]] (8)\n* [[Ayaka Hirahara]] (8)\n* [[Ayumi Hamasaki]] (15)\n* [[BoA]] (6)\n* [[Chemistry (band)|Chemistry]] (5)\n* [[Chisato Moritaka]] (6)\n* [[Da Pump]] (6)\n* [[Dreams Come True (band)|Dreams Come True]] (15)\n* [[E-girls]] (5)\n* [[Every Little Thing (band)|Every Little Thing]] (8)\n* [[Exile (Japanese band)|EXILE]] (12)\n* [[Four Leaves]] (7)\n* [[Gackt]] (5)\n* [[Gospellers]] (6)\n* [[Hikaru Genji (band)|Hikaru Genji]] (6)\n* [[Hiroko Moriguchi]] (6)\n* [[Hiromi Go]] (31)\n* [[Hiromi Iwasaki (singer)|Hiromi Iwasaki]] (14)\n* [[Ikimono-gakari]] (10)\n* [[Junko Sakurada]] (9)\n* [[Kana Nishino]] (9)\n* [[Ken Hirai]] (8)\n* [[Kobukuro]] (7)\n* [[Kome Kome Club]] (5)\n* [[Kumi Koda]] (8)\n* [[Ky\u014dko Koizumi]] (5)\n* [[L'Arc~en~Ciel]] (5)\n* [[Linda Yamamoto]] (5)\n* [[Masaharu Fukuyama]] (11)\n* [[Mayumi Itsuwa]] (5)\n* [[MAX (band)|MAX]] (5)\n* [[Miho Nakayama]] (7) \n* [[Mika Nakashima]] (9) \t \n* [[Momoe Yamaguchi]] (6)\n* [[Morning Musume]] (10)\n* [[Namie Amuro]] (9)\n* [[Nana Mizuki]] (6)\n* Naoko Kawai (\u6cb3\u5408\u5948\u4fdd\u5b50) (6)\n* Naomi Sagara (\u4f50\u826f\u76f4\u7f8e) (13)\n* [[Perfume (Japanese band)|Perfume]] (11)\n* [[Porno Graffitti]] (11)\n* [[Akemi Cynthia Paule Uchima|Saori Minami]] (8)\n* [[Sandaime J Soul Brothers]] (7)\n* [[Seiko Matsuda]] (22)\n* [[Sekai no Owari]] (5)\n* [[Sexy Zone]] (6)\n* [[SMAP]] (23)\n* [[Tokio (band)|TOKIO]] (24)\n* [[Tomomi Kahala]] (5)\n* [[T.M.Revolution]] (5)\n* [[W-inds.]] (6)\n* [[X Japan]] (8)\n* [[Yo Hitoto]] (5)\n* [[Y\u014dko Oginome]] (5)\n* [[Yuzu (band)|Yuzu]] (8)\n{{Div col end}}\n\n<span style=\"font-size:87%;\">1. Matsuura has also appeared with [[DEF.DIVA]] and [[GAM (group)|GAM]]. However, NHK does not count those appearances towards her count.</span>\n\n==== Enka and other contemporary ====\n{{Div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* Aya Shimazu (\u5cf6\u6d25\u4e9c\u77e2) (5)\n* [[Ayako Fuji]] (21)\n* [[Akiko Wada]] (39)\n* [[Akira Fuse]] (25)\n* [[Chiyoko Shimakura]] (35)\n* [[Fuyumi Sakamoto]] (30)\n* George Yamamoto (\u5c71\u672c\u8b72\u4e8c) (11)\n* [[Harumi Miyako]] (29)\n* [[Hibari Misora]] (18)\n* [[Hideaki Tokunaga]] (10)\n* [[Hideki Saij\u014d]] (18)\n* [[Hiroshi Itsuki]] (48)\n* Ichir\u014d Toba (\u9ce5\u7fbd\u4e00\u90ce) (20)\n* [[Kaori Kozai]] (19)\n* [[Kaori Mizumori]] (16)\n* [[Kenichi Mikawa]] (26)\n* [[Kenji Sawada]] (17)\n* [[Kiyoshi Hikawa]] (19)\n* [[Kiyoshi Maekawa]] (18)\n* [[Masako Mori (singer)|Masako Mori]] (15)\n* [[Masao Sen]] (\u5343 \u660c\u592b) (19)\n* [[Masashi Sada]] (19)\n* [[Mina Aoe]] (18)\n* Mitsuko Nakamura (\u4e2d\u6751\u7f8e\u5f8b\u5b50) (15)\n* [[Miyuki Kawanaka]] (24)\n* Natsuko Godai (\u4f0d\u4ee3\u590f\u5b50) (22)\n* [[Rimi Natsukawa]] (6)\n* [[Ry\u014dko Moriyama]] (10)\n* [[Sabur\u014d Kitajima]] (50)\n* [[Sachiko Kobayashi]] (33)\n* [[Saori Yuki]] and Sachiko Yasuda (10)<sup>1</sup>\n* Saori Yuki (13)\n* [[Sayuri Ishikawa]] (41)\n* [[Shinichi Mori]] (48)\n* [[Shinji Tanimura]] (16)\n* [[Takao Horiuchi]] (17)\n* [[Takashi Hosokawa]] (39)\n* [[Y\u014dko Nagayama]] (14)\n* [[Yoshimi Tendo]] (23)\n* Yutaka Yamakawa (\u5c71\u5ddd\u8c4a) (11)\n{{Div col end}}\n\n<span style=\"font-size:87%;\">1. Saori Yuki and Sachiko Yasuda are counted as a duet. Solo appearances by either of the two would not count towards the duet count.</span>\n\n===Foreigners===\nAlthough ''K\u014dhaku'' is made up of mostly Japanese entertainers, foreign artists (artists who are not Japanese nationals) popular in Japan have competed in the program. Special appearances, supporting musicians or other methods of participation where the artist or group's performance was not accounted for in the overall scoring should not be added to this list. Below is a list of artists or groups who have done so, categorized based on the country of origin (Asian or non-Asian) the person or majority of the members in a group are from, along with the editions:\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-1-of-2}}\n====Asian====\n* [[Agnes Chan]] (Hong Kong, 24th through 26th)\n* [[AKB48 Team TP]] (Taiwan, 70th)\n* [[AKB48 Team SH]] (China, 70th)\n* [[Alan Tam]] (Hong Kong, 40th)\n* [[BoA]] (South Korea, 53rd through 58th)\n* [[BNK48]] (Thailand, 69th and 70th)\n* [[CGM48]] (Thailand, 70th)\n* [[Cho Yong-Pil]] (South Korea, 38th through 41st)\n* [[DEL48]] (India, 70th)\n* [[Dick Lee]], [[Lim Hyung-joo]], [[:ja:\u8a31\u53ef (\u4e8c\u80e1\u594f\u8005)|Xu Ke]], and [[:ja:amin|Amin]] (Singapore, South Korea, and China respectively, 56th)\n* [[Gary Valenciano]] (Philippines, 41st)\n* [[Girls' Generation]] (South Korea, 62nd)\n* [[JKT48]] (Indonesia, 70th)\n* [[Judy Ongg]] (Taiwan, 30th and 31st)\n* [[Kara (South Korean band)|KARA]] (South Korea, 62nd)\n* [[:ko:\uacc4\uc740\uc219|Kye Eun-sook]] (South Korea, 39th through 45th)\n* [[Lee Jung Hyun]] (South Korea, 55th)\n* [[MNL48]] (Philippines, 70th)\n* [[:ja:\u6b27\u967d\u83f2\u83f2|Ouyang Feifei]] (Taiwan, 23rd, 24th and 42nd)\n* [[Oyunaa]] (Mongolia, 41st)\n* [[Patti Kim (singer)|Patti Kim]] (South Korea, 40th)\n* [[:ko:Ryu (\uac00\uc218)|Ryu]] (South Korea, 55th)\n* [[SGO48]] (Vietnam, 70th)\n* [[Smokey Mountain (band)|Smokey Mountain]] (Philippines, 42nd)\n* [[Teresa Teng]] (Taiwan, 36th, 37th and 42nd)\n* [[TVXQ]] (South Korea, 59th, 60th and 62nd)\n* [[Twice (band)|TWICE]] (South Korea, 68th, 69th and 70th)\n* [[Twelve Girls Band]] (China, 54th)\n* [[Vivian Hsu]] (Taiwan, 49th)\n* [[:ko:\uae40\uc5f0\uc790|Yonja Kim]] (South Korea, 40th, 45th, 52nd)\n\n{{col-2-of-2}}\n\n====Non-Asian====\n<!--Idina Menzel and Lady Gaga were neutral performers, not competitors. This list is for competitors only.-->\n* [[Alexander Gradsky]] (Russia, 41st)\n* [[Alfredo Casero]] ([[Argentina]], 53rd)\n* [[Alyson Williams]] (United States, 41st)\n* [[Andy Williams]] (United States, 42nd)\n* [[Chris Hart (musician)|Chris Hart]] (United States, 64th and 65th)\n* [[Cyndi Lauper]] (United States, 41st)\n* [[James Shigeta]] (United States, 8th and 9th)\n* [[Jero]] (United States, 59th and 60th)\n* [[John Ken Nuzzo]] (United States, 53rd and 55th)\n* [[Laima Vaikule]] ([[Latvia]], 42nd)\n* [[Leah Dizon]] (United States, 58th)\n* [[:ja:\u30de\u30eb\u30b7\u30a2|M\u00e1rcia]] ([[Brazil]], 41st)\n* [[Paul Simon]] (United States, 41st)\n* [[Rosanna Zambon]] (Italy, 21st and 22nd)\n* [[Sarah Brightman]] (United Kingdom, 42nd and 69th)\n* [[The Ventures]] (United States, 42nd)\n{{col-end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www1.nhk.or.jp/kouhaku/ K\u014dhaku Uta Gassen Official Page (Japanese)]\n*[http://www.nhk.or.jp/digitalmuseum/nhk50years_en/categories/p54/ NHK K\u014dhaku on the NHK Digital Museum]\n\n{{navboxes\n| list1 = {{K\u014dhaku Uta Gassen events}}\n{{New Year}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kohaku Uta Gassen}}\n[[Category:NHK K\u014dhaku Uta Gassen]]\n[[Category:Music competitions in Japan]]\n[[Category:Japanese music television series]]\n[[Category:Japanese television specials]]\n[[Category:1953 Japanese television series debuts]]\n[[Category:New Year's television specials]]\n[[Category:Annual television programs]]\n[[Category:1950s Japanese television series]]\n[[Category:Music festivals in Japan]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=September 2018}}\n{{short description|Television program}}\n{{Expand Japanese|NHK\u7d05\u767d\u6b4c\u5408\u6226|date=December 2014}}\n{{infobox television\n| show_name                = NHK K\u014dhaku Uta Gassen\n| image                    = [[File:NHK Kouhaku logo.svg|220px]]<br />Logo since the [[58th NHK K\u014dhaku Uta Gassen|58th edition]] (2007)\n[[File:Kouhaku_Hosts_from_2013.png|237px]]<br />The hosts of the [[58th NHK K\u014dhaku Uta Gassen|64th edition]] (2013)\n| audio_format             = <!--[[Surround sound|5.1 Surround Sound]]-->\n| runtime                  = 4 hours 30 minutes\n| creator                  = Tsumoru Kondo\n| presenter                = ''Various (see [[#Results|below]])''\n| language                 = Japanese\n| endtheme                 = [[Auld Lang Syne|Hotaru no hikari]]\n| num_episodes             = <onlyinclude>69</onlyinclude> contests\n| location                 = [[Tokyo Takarazuka Theater]] (1959\u20131972)<br>[[NHK Hall]] (1973\u20132019; 2022 onwards)<br>[[Tokyo International Forum]] (2021)\n| picture_format           = [[480i]] (SDTV) (1953\u20132011) <br/> [[1080i]] (HDTV) (2000\u2013present) <br/>[[2160p]] (4K) (2018\u2013present) <br/> [[4320p]] (8K) (2018\u2013present)\n| company                  = NHK\n| country                  = Japan\n| network                  = [[NHK General TV]] (1953\u2013present)<br>[[NHK Radio 1]] (1951\u2013present)<br>[[NHK World Premium]] {{small|(Worldwide)}} (1964\u2013present)\n| first_aired              = {{start date|1951|1|3}}\n| last_aired               = present\n| website                  = http://www1.nhk.or.jp/kouhaku/\n| website_title            = Official website\n}}\n{{nihongo|'''''NHK K\u014dhaku Uta Gassen'''''|NHK\u7d05\u767d\u6b4c\u5408\u6226|Enueichikei K\u014dhaku Uta Gassen; \"''NHK Red and White Song Battle''\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2017/11/16/music/twice-daichi-miura-among-10-debuts-years-kohaku/ |title=Twice and Daichi Miura among 10 debuts at this year\u2019s \u2018Kohaku\u2019 |last=Smith |first=Alyssa I. |work=[[The Japan Times]] |date=November 16, 2017 |access-date=September 13, 2018}}</ref>}}, more commonly known simply as '''''K\u014dhaku''''', is an annual [[New Year's Eve]] [[television special]] produced by Japanese public broadcaster [[NHK]]. It is broadcast live simultaneously on television and radio, nationally and internationally by the NHK network and by some overseas (mainly cable) broadcasters who buy the program. The show ends shortly before midnight. Before the show began broadcasting on television in late 1953, the show was held on 3 January and only consisted of a radio broadcast.\n\nThe program divides the most popular music artists of the year into competing teams of red and white. The \"red\" team or {{nihongo|''akagumi''|\u8d64\u7d44, \u7d05\u7d44|}} is composed of all female artists (or groups with female vocals), while the \"white\" team or {{nihongo|''shirogumi''|\u767d\u7d44|}} is all male (or groups with male vocals). At the end of the show, judges and the audience vote to decide which group performed better.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2016/01/02/national/media-national/nhk-sees-ratings-for-kohaku-music-show-sink-to-lowest-ever/ |title=NHK sees ratings for \u2018Kohaku\u2019 music show sink to lowest ever |work=The Japan Times |date=January 2, 2016 |access-date=September 13, 2018}}</ref> The honor of performing on ''K\u014dhaku'' is strictly by invitation, so only the most successful singing acts in the Japanese entertainment industry can perform. In addition to the actual music performances, the costumes, hair-styles, makeup, dancing, and lighting are important. Even today, a performance on ''K\u014dhaku'' is said to be a big highlight in a singer's career because of the show's wide reach.\n\n==Song selection process==\nThe songs and performers are examined by a selection committee put together by NHK. The basis for selection are record sales and adaptability to the edition's theme.\n\nAt the same time, a [[demographic]] survey is conducted regarding the most popular singers for each and what kind of music people want to hear. This and the song selection explain the [[wikt:amalgamation|amalgamation]] of the [[List of music styles|musical genres]] and its [[artist]]s.\n\nThere are, however, exceptions to the process. [[Momoe Yamaguchi]] chose to sing her favorite song \"Hito Natsu no Keiken\" (\u3072\u3068\u590f\u306e\u7d4c\u9a13) with its suggestive lyrics during the 25th edition, despite NHK's pick of a different song.\n\n==Show==\n[[File:Kohaku1953.jpg|thumb|right|The competitors of the 4th K\u014dhaku Uta Gassen (1953)]]\nWhen the show was first broadcast on radio in 1951, each team had a few performers, all of whom would perform within an hour. Since 1989, the program goes on for at least four hours as both teams, each having at least 25 performers, perform their songs.\n\nAt the end of the show, the audience and a panel of judges&mdash;notable celebrities who may or may not have a connection to the music industry&mdash;vote to select the winning team. In the past, the audience vote has been composed of a head count of the venue audience members, who can vote for either team ([[NHK Hall]], which has been the venue for most ''K\u014dhaku'' editions since 1971, can seat 3,000 people). This counted as one vote.\n\nAs of the 54th (2003) and 55th editions (2004), viewers who watch the program through [[ISDB#ISDB-S|ISDB-S]] on NHK BS Hi-vision could vote by having their own head count in their respective households. Although it is still sketchy to determine in the 55th, the audience vote is counted as two votes: one for the venue audience and one for ISDB-S viewers.\n\nThe audience vote(s) are added to those of the judges who each have to vote for one team. The team with the most votes wins.\n\nThe above process was done differently for the 56th edition (2005). Instead, the NHK Hall head count, the vote count from cellphone users and the vote count from ISDB-S viewers each counted as one vote. As stated above, the team that got at least two votes won.\n\nIn the [[57th NHK K\u014dhaku Uta Gassen|57th edition]] (2006), aside from cellphone and ISDB-S viewers and the NHK Hall audience, [[1seg]] users voted. Its format had been reverted to the ball voting system&mdash;from the audience head count and the judges' votes.\n\nFrom the [[58th NHK K\u014dhaku Uta Gassen|58th edition]] (2007) to the 63rd edition (2012) and again in the 65th (2014), 66th (2015), and 68th editions (2017), the winner was determined through an overall head count, all from cellphone, ISDB-S viewers, 1seg users, and the NHK Hall Audience (including guests). Voting reverted temporarily to judges plus audience-unit votes in the 64th edition (2013) and 67th (2016) except that viewing audience votes (from internet, cellphone, digital TV, and 1seg voting) during halftime and end of show would each count as one vote and the NHK Hall head count as another single vote.\n\nAside from the performances, there are special performances where certain performers do their act together, and the so-called \"Ring Show\" where performers from both teams take part in a \"singing exercise.\" At the end of the show, all the performers sing \"[[Hotaru no Hikari]]\" (\u86cd\u306e\u5149) together. The song is based on the Scottish \"[[Auld Lang Syne]]\" that is commonly sung at New Year parties in the west.\n\n==Results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! No. !! Date !! style=\"background:red; color:white\" | Red team host !! style=\"background:white; color:rgb(195, 141, 61)\" | White team host !! style=\"background:gold\" | Mediator !! Winning<br>team !! Overall record\n|-\n! colspan=\"7\" style=\"color:white; background:darkblue;\" | SHOWA PERIOD EVENTS\n|-\n! [[1st NHK K\u014dhaku Uta Gassen|1]]\n| 3 January 1951 || [[Michiko Kat\u014d]] || [[Shuuichi Fujikura]]|| Masaharu Tanabe || style=\"background:white; color:rgb(195, 141, 61)\" | White || 1-0\n|-\n! [[2nd NHK K\u014dhaku Uta Gassen|2]]\n| 3 January 1952 || [[Kiyoko Tange]] || Shuuichi Fujikura || Masaharu Tanabe || style=\"background:white; color:rgb(195, 141, 61)\" | White || 2-0\n|-\n! [[3rd NHK K\u014dhaku Uta Gassen|3]]\n| 2 January 1953 || Suga Honda || [[Teru Miyata]] || Masayori Shimura || style=\"background:white; color:rgb(195, 141, 61)\" | White || 3-0\n|-\n! [[4th NHK K\u014dhaku Uta Gassen|4]]\n| 31 December 1953 || [[Takiko Mizunoe]] || [[Keizo Takahashi]]|| Seigoro Kitade || style=\"background:red; color:white\" | Red || 3-1\n|-\n! [[5th NHK K\u014dhaku Uta Gassen|5]]\n| 31 December 1954 || [[Natsue Fukuji]] || Keizo Takahashi|| Sh\u014dzabur\u014d Ishii || style=\"background:red; color:white\" | Red ||3-2\n|-\